<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<recipe>
    <name>Chicken, Coconut And Galangal Soup (TOM KI-IAA KAI)</name>
    <indexCharacter>C</indexCharacter>
    <notes>THIS IS ONE OF THE CLASSIC SOUPS OF THAILAND. THE THAI NAME MEANS ‘BOILED GALANGAL CHICKEN’. ALTHOUGH USUALLY MADE WITH CHICKEN, YOU CAN MAKE THIS RECIPE USING PRAWNS, FISH OR VEGETABLES. DON’T WORRY WHEN THE COCONUT MILK SPLITS — IT IS SUPPOSED TO.</notes>
    <servings>4</servings>
    <instructions>PUT the coconut milk, lemon grass, galangal and
shallots in a saucepan or wok over a medium heat
and bring to a boil.

ADD the chicken, fish sauce and palm sugar and
simmer, stirring constantly for 5 minutes or until
the chicken is cooked through.

ADD the tomatoes and mushrooms and simmer
for 2 to 3 minutes. Add the lime juice, kaffir lime
leaves and chillies in the last few seconds, taking
care not to let the tomatoes lose their shape.
Taste, then adjust the seasoning if necessary. This
dish is not meant to be overwhelmingly hot, but to
have a sweet, salty, sour taste. Serve garnished
with coriander leaves.</instructions>
    <ingredients>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>3</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>c</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>coconut milk</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions></processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>2</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>ea</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>lemon grass stalks</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions> white part only, each cut into a tassel or bruised</processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>2</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>in</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>piece of galangal</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions> cut into several pieces</processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>4</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>ea</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>Asian shallots</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions> smashed with the flat side of a cleaver</processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>14</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>oz</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>skinless chicken breast fillets</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions> cut into slices</processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>2</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>T</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>fish sauce</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions></processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>1</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>T</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>palm sugar</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions></processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>7</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>oz</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>baby tomatoes</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions> cut into bite—sized pieces if large</processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>5</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>oz</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>straw mushrooms</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions></processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>3</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>T</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>lime juice</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions></processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>6</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>ea</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>kaffir lime leaves</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions> torn in half</processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>4</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>ea</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>bird's eye chillies</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions> stems removed, bruised</processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
        <ingredient>
            <quantity>0</quantity>
            <unitOfMeasure>-</unitOfMeasure>
            <ingredientName>coriander (cilantro) leaves</ingredientName>
            <processingInstructions> for garnish</processingInstructions>
        </ingredient>
    </ingredients>
</recipe>
